                                                          ======================================================
                                                            Java String - Point 2: String Literal vs new String()
                                                          ======================================================
Main Topic:
-----------
In Java, we can create String in two common ways:

String s = "java";

and

String s = new String("java");

Both look similar, but internally memory behavior is different.

1. String Literal

Code
String s = "java";
String t = "java";

Memory Diagram
STACK MEMORY                         HEAP MEMORY
--------------------                 --------------------------
main() stack frame                    String Pool
                                      --------------------------
s  -------- reference ------------\
                                    \
                                     ---->  "java"
                                    /
t  -------- reference ------------/
--------------------                 --------------------------

Step-by-step Explanation

Step 1
------
String s = "java";
JVM checks the String Pool.If "java" is not present, JVM creates "java" inside the String Pool.

Then s points to "java".

Step 2
String t = "java";

JVM again checks the String Pool.

Now "java" is already present.

So JVM will not create a new object.

t will also point to the same "java" object.

Important Point

s and t are two different reference variables in stack memory.But both are pointing to the same "java" object in String Pool.
Output
System.out.println(s == t);
System.out.println(s.equals(t));

Output:
true
true

Reason

s == t → true

Because both references point to the same String Pool object.

s.equals(t) → true
Because both have the same content: "java".

2. Using new String()

Code

String s = new String("java");
String t = new String("java");

Memory Diagram
STACK MEMORY                         HEAP MEMORY
--------------------                 ------------------------------
main() stack frame                    Normal Heap Area
                                      ------------------------------
s  -------- reference ------------>   Object 1: "java"

t  -------- reference ------------>   Object 2: "java"


                                      String Pool
                                      ------------------------------
                                      "java"
--------------------                 ------------------------------

Explanation

new keyword always creates a new object in heap memory.

s points to one object.
t points to another object.

Both objects have the same value "java",
but both are different objects in memory.
Output
System.out.println(s == t);
System.out.println(s.equals(t));

Output:

false
true
Reason
s == t → false
Because s and t point to different heap objects.

s.equals(t) → true
Because both have the same content: "java".
3. Mixed Case
Code
String s = "java";
String t = new String("java");
Memory Diagram
STACK MEMORY                         HEAP MEMORY
--------------------                 ------------------------------
main() stack frame                    String Pool
                                      ------------------------------
s  -------- reference ------------>   "java"


                                      Normal Heap Area
                                      ------------------------------
t  -------- reference ------------>   new String object: "java"
--------------------                 ------------------------------
Explanation
s points to the "java" object inside String Pool.

t points to a new String object inside normal heap memory.

Both have the same content,
but both are different objects.
Output
System.out.println(s == t);
System.out.println(s.equals(t));

Output:

false
true
Reason
s == t → false
Because s points to String Pool object,
but t points to a new heap object.

s.equals(t) → true
Because both have the same content: "java".
4. Difference Between == and equals()
==
== checks reference / object location.

Example:

String s = "java";
String t = "java";

System.out.println(s == t);

Output:

true

Because both point to the same object in String Pool.

equals()
equals() checks actual content / text.

Example:

String s = new String("java");
String t = new String("java");

System.out.println(s.equals(t));

Output:

true

Because both have the same text: "java".

5. Final Comparison Table
Code	== Result	equals() Result	Reason
String s = "java"; String t = "java";	true	true	Same String Pool object
String s = new String("java"); String t = new String("java");	false	true	Different heap objects, same content
String s = "java"; String t = new String("java");	false	true	One pool object, one heap object, same content
6. Main Rules to Remember
String literal uses String Pool.

new String() creates a new object in heap memory.

== compares reference / object location.

equals() compares actual content / text.

For String content comparison, always use equals().
7. Interview Answer

In Java, String literals are stored in the String Pool.

When we create two Strings with the same literal value, Java reuses the same object from the String Pool.

Example:

String s = "java";
String t = "java";

Here, both s and t point to the same "java" object in String Pool.

That is why:

s == t

returns true.

But when we use new String():

String s = new String("java");
String t = new String("java");

Java creates new objects in heap memory.

So s == t returns false, because both references point to different objects.

But s.equals(t) returns true, because the actual content is the same.

8. One-line Memory Summary
String s = "java";

s = reference variable in stack memory
"java" = actual object in String Pool inside heap memory
String s = new String("java");

s = reference variable in stack memory
new String object = normal heap memory
"java" literal = String Pool
9. Final Short Note
For String literals with the same value, Java reuses the same object from String Pool.

So s and t are different variables in stack,
but both can point to the same object in String Pool.

Use == only when you want to compare references.

Use equals() when you want to compare actual String content.
                                                                        
