So, System.out.println(s == t);  -->  OUTPUT: True      :: Because both s and t point to the same object. :: 

How JVM works with String Pool?

Code:

        String s = "java";
        String t = "java";
Step 1
--------
String s = "java";

JVM checks String Pool:  Is "java" already present in String Pool? Answer:

No

So JVM creates "java" in String Pool.

s ---> "java"

Step 2


String t = "java"; JVM again checks String Pool:   Is "java" already present in String Pool?

Answer:
Yes

So JVM does not create a new object. It simply gives the same reference to t.

s ---> "java"
t ---> same "java"


There is only one String Pool area, not a new String Pool for every String.

Example:

String a = "java";
String b = "java";

String c = "python";
String d = "python";


                                                          Memory:
                                                          ========

                                                          STACK MEMORY                         HEAP MEMORY
                                                          --------------------                 --------------------------
                                                          main() stack frame                    String Pool
                                                                                                --------------------------
                                                          a  -------- reference ------------\
                                                                                              \
                                                                                               ----> "java"
                                                                                              /
                                                          b  -------- reference ------------/
                                                          
                                                          
                                                          c  -------- reference ------------\
                                                                                              \
                                                                                               ----> "python"
                                                                                              /
                                                          d  -------- reference ------------/
                                                          --------------------                 --------------------------

There is one String Pool.
Same literal value reuses same object.
Different literal value creates different object inside the same String Pool.


Interview explanation : 
======================

String Pool is a special area inside heap memory where Java stores String literals.
When we create a String using literal syntax, JVM first checks the String Pool.
If the same value already exists, JVM reuses the existing object.
If the value does not exist, JVM creates a new object in the String Pool.
This saves memory because duplicate String literals are not created again and again.

